"Oetken M., Jagodzinski L.S., Vogt C., Jochum A., Oehlmann J.","Combined effects of chemical and temperature stress on Chironomus riparius populations with differing genetic variability",2009,"Journal of Environmental Science and Health - Part A Toxic/Hazardous Substances and Environmental Engineering","44","10",,"955","962",,,10.1080/10934520902996849,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70350437882&partnerID=40&md5=153d01650991f26f5e9db7011d4495e4","Institute for Ecology, Evolution and Diversity, Goethe University, Siesmayerstrasse 70, D-60323 Frankfurt am Main, Germany","Oetken, M., Institute for Ecology, Evolution and Diversity, Goethe University, Siesmayerstrasse 70, D-60323 Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Jagodzinski, L.S., Institute for Ecology, Evolution and Diversity, Goethe University, Siesmayerstrasse 70, D-60323 Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Vogt, C., Institute for Ecology, Evolution and Diversity, Goethe University, Siesmayerstrasse 70, D-60323 Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Jochum, A., Institute for Ecology, Evolution and Diversity, Goethe University, Siesmayerstrasse 70, D-60323 Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Oehlmann, J., Institute for Ecology, Evolution and Diversity, Goethe University, Siesmayerstrasse 70, D-60323 Frankfurt am Main, Germany","Exposure to pollutants under multiple environmental stressors (e.g., climate change and global warming) and the genetic diversity of populations are suspected to have serious impacts on populations and ecosystems but have only rarely been analysed. In the present study, we investigated the effects of the biocide tributyltin (TBT) within a temperature gradient (17, 20 and 23C) on life history parameters of a genetically diverse (GEN+) and a highly inbred population (GEN-) of the midge Chironomus riparius. While endpoints, mortality and reproduction parameters were considered, the population growth rate as an integrative endpoint was determined. We found severe effects for GEN-, indicating that populations with lower genetic diversity are more endangered by combined stressors such as increasing temperature and chemical pollution compared to genetically diverse populations.","Chironomidae; Climate change; Environmental stressors; Extinction risk; Genetic impoverishment; Life history parameters; Tributyltin","Chironomidae; Environmental stressors; Extinction risks; Life history; Tributyltin; Global warming; biocide; biocide tributyltin; unclassified drug; DNA; microsatellite DNA; organotin compound; tributyltin; animal experiment; article; chemical stress; Chironomidae; controlled study; environmental exposure; female; genetic variability; growth rate; inbred strain; male; mortality; nonhuman; population growth; reproduction; species extinction; temperature; temperature stress; animal; clutch size; drug effect; environmental exposure; genetics; greenhouse effect; growth, development and aging; heat; life cycle; longevity; physiological stress; physiology; water pollutant; Chironomidae; Chironomus riparius; Animals; Chironomidae; Clutch Size; DNA; Environmental Exposure; Female; Greenhouse Effect; Hot Temperature; Life Cycle Stages; Longevity; Male; Microsatellite Repeats; Reproduction; Stress, Physiological; Trialkyltin Compounds; Water Pollutants, Chemical",,"DNA, 9007-49-2; tributyltin, 688-73-3; DNA, 9007-49-2; Trialkyltin Compounds; Water Pollutants, Chemical; tributyltin, 688-73-3",,,,"Loreau, M., Oteng-Yeboah, A., Arroyo, M.T.K., Babin, D., Barbault, R., Donoghue, M., Gadgil, M., Watson, R.T., Diversity without representation (2006) Nature, 442, pp. 245-246; Nowak, C., Vogt, C., Pfenninger, M., Oehlmann, J., Streit, B., Schwenk, K., Oetken, M., Rapid genetic erosion in pollutantexposed experimental chironomid populations (2009) Environ. Pollut., 157, pp. 881-887; (2007) Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis - Summary for Policymakers Intergovernmental Panel on ClimateChange, , http://www.ipcc.ch/SPM2feb07.pdf, (accessed March 2009); Heinonen, J., Honkanen,